 followers who, while differing in their goals and tactics, nonetheless came together as Chicanos and reformers. Deftly combining personal recollection and interviews of movement participants with an array of archival, newspaper, and secondary sources, Chávez provides an absorbing account of the events that constituted the Los Angeles-based Chicano movement. At the same time he offers insights into the emergence and the fate of the movement elsewhere. He presents a critical analysis of the concept of Chicano nationalism, an idea shared by all leaders of the insurgency, and places it within a larger global and comparative framework. Examining such variables as gender, class, age, and power relationships, this book offers a sophisticated consideration of how ethnic nationalism and identity functioned in the United States during the 1960s and 1970s.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCivil rights movementszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy20th century. 0aEthnic identity. 0aMexican AmericansxCivil rightszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMexican AmericanszCaliforniazLos AngelesxEthnic identity. 0aMexican AmericanszCaliforniazLos AngelesxPolitics and governmenty20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / West (AK, CA, CO, HI, ID, MT, NV, UT, WY).2bisacsh  a1960s.  a1970s.  abrown berets.  achicana.  achicano movement.  achicano.  aclass.  aclassism.  acultural history.  acultural studies.  aethnic identity.  agender studies.  aglobal.  alatin america.  alatin american history.  alatin american.  alatinx.  alos angeles.  amexican culture.  amexican heritage.  amexico city.  anationalism.  areformation.  areformers.  aregional history.  asocial history.  asocial studies.  asouth america.  asouthern california.  awest co